76561198007300752,Not Recommended,227060,11755785,"Posted: 17 August, 2014",all,Blackadar,"Let's start out positive. It's an attractive game with a wonderful map, some decent strategic options, a good basis for gameplay (it's a wonderful time period for war games) and has nice music. They did a great job with the historical setting and it has a complex recruitment/supply system that can take some time to master. There are a lot of things going for Hegemony Rome.It's also an exercise in futility and frustration.The logistics/supply system isn't well explained at all beyond how to link a city forward. There's no explanation of why this is important, how to do it well, how to link cities together and so forth. Building and promotions haven't been explained at all and I have no idea what they are. Needless to say, there's a learning curve with scant few resources from which to learn.I can get by that. I can't get by some of the gameplay. For instance, the second scenario requires you to take on 18 enemy units from Germany. There's no way my units can do this - they fold instantly and the TBS mechanics are awful so it's just a massive mob. Unlike the Total War games, this is just mob warfare.The real issue is trying to keep even half that many units in supply while raiders continually raid from areas of the map I'm not allowed to enter (and no, you can't station a unit at the entry point because there's no supply there), I've had one city mysteriously taken over by bandits TWICE with 2 of my units in the city and never any pop up that told me I was even being attacked.Those are all fundamental gameplay issues that have no business being in a final product. In one scenario we get balance issues, gameplay issues, UI issues...all rolled into one mess. Trying to untangle some of this might be possible but there's not even a manual. So about those concepts that aren't explained? You're screwed.That's not even mentioning the three crashes I encountered playing this battle.Come on, devs. You could have had a good product here. But you've got to do the polishing that's required. That means polishing the balance, providing the documentation needed by the player and fixing the bugs (rather than releasing new DLC)."
